Real World Random Forest

Business Problem

Based on a number of factors, a Healthcare organization wants to build a predictive model for Heart Disease. Using determinants like Age, Blood pressure, Chest Pain, Maximum Heart Rate, etc., they would like to identify those with likely Heart Disease for deeper diagnostic testing, lifestyle intervention and potential corrective surgery.

Since there are numerous observable factors (12+) that have historically shown the significant correlation to Heart Disease, the organization will develop a Random Forest model to provide the highest predictive accuracy.

Goal

Using an existing dataset of Heart Disease observation, determine the highest accuracy model to predict Heart Disease for new patients where the model features are available.

Tools

R-Studio with libraries: tidyverse, randomforest, ggplot2, cowplot

Steps

1. Import data from UCI machine learning datasets @ http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.cleveland.data

2. Clean and recode the data features as needed to use for Random Forest modeling

3. Impute missing values in the dataset usimg a number of random forest iterations and then Model ‘HeartDisease’ from a Forest of 500 Random Trees using all features from the dataset

4. Review the model for the OOB (‘out of bag’) error rate. Above we see that it is 16.8%. This means that 84.2% of the samples were correctly classified by this random forest model. The confusion matrix tells us that 27 Unhealthy Patients that were incorrectly classified by the model as Healthy - and 23 Healthy patients that were classified as Unhealthy. Let’s plot the error rates to see if we might improve the model with more trees

5. We can review the plot and see if we are in fact lowering our error rate as more trees are evaluated byt the model.

Here, The BLUE line represents our error rate when classifying Unhealthy patients, the RED line our error rate when classifying Healthy patients and the GREEN line is the overall OOB error rate.

6. We can rerun the model with more trees and also experiment with the number of variables used at each internal node split.

This will help us confirm if we can reduce the OOB error rate and thus improve the accuracy of the model. In this case, more trees are of little help as the error rate stabilizes after about 500 Trees. Note the plot below for 1000 trees and the similarity to the graph above for 500 Trees.

Notice the OOB error rate for the 1000 tree model is actually higher than the 500 tree model. Also I tried adding additonal variables at each node step and doing so did not improve the accuracy in this particular case.
